                                                    BRANCHING

TOPIC: IF-ELSE STATEMENT

    Vocabs:
    -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    + Equality operator: (==) evaluates TRUE if the left and right side are equal.
        - Statements in the branch must be indented, typically 4 spaces.
    + Inequality Operator: (!=) meaning not equal.
    -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    IF -> executes one group of statements when an expression is true.
    ELSE -> another group of statements when the expression is false.

    if name == "Armando":       |   name = "Armando"
        1st execution           |
    else:                       |
        2nd execution           |

Multi_branch if-else statement -
    + An if-else statement can be extended to have 3 of more branches by using if -> elif -> else!
        - elif means else-if.
    + Each branch expression is checked in sequence. As soon as one branch expression found to be true,
      that branch will execute.
    + If no expression is True, the else branch executes.

    if expression1:
        statements for first branch
    elif expression2:
        statements for second branch
    else:
        statements for else branch

.......................................................................................................................

TOPIC: DETECTING RANGES WITH BRANCHES

Relational Operators -

    -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    + Relational Operator: checks how one operand's value relates to another (< | > | ==)
    -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    Relational Operator | Description                                   | Example (x = 3)
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
            <           | a < b means a is less than b                  | x < 4 (true) | x < 3 (false)
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
            >           | a > b means a is greater than b               | x > 2 (true) | x > 3 (false)
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
            <=          | a <= b means a is less than or equal to b     | x <= 4 (true) | x <= 3 (true) | x <= 2 (false)
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
            >=          | a >= b means a is greater than or equal to b  | x >= 2 (true) | x >= 3 (true) | x >= 4 (false)
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Operator Chaining - Python supports operator chaining.

    | a < b < c |: Chaining performs comparisons left to right.
        + Evaluating a < b (if result is true) b < c (evaluated next)
        + If the first comparison results to false, no need for next evaluation.
        + a is not compared to c.

.......................................................................................................................

TOPIC: LOGICAL OPERATORS

    -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    + Logical operator: treats operands as being True or False.
        - Includes AND, OR, NOT.
    + Boolean: refers to a value that is either true or false.
        - True and False are keywords and must be capitalized.
    -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    Logical Operator    |   Description
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        a and b         | AND: True when both of its operands are TRUE.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        a or b          | OR: True when at least one of its two operands are TRUE.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        not a           | NOT: True when its one operand is FALSE, vice versa.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    Example:

        if (statement):
            print("....")
        elif (statement) and (statement):
            print("....")
        else:
            print("....")